CatDescriptText: Cutline of image published in Pittsburgh Courier newspaper, October 20 ,1962, pg. 4, reads: "Arson Suspected in Fire - Suspicion of a deliberate firing of the three-story frame house (note white front porch pillars) at 7028 Frankstown Ave. Monday night at 10:30, led the police bomb and arson squad to investigate the six-alarm blaze which destroyed $10,000 worth of property. Next-door neighbors had warned police of prowlers on the premises, about 9:30 P. M., but a prompt police search was futile.  The smell of burning gasoline by Mrs. Albert C. Wynn, at 7030 Frankstown at 10 P.M. led her to turn in alarm. Firemen attacked the flames from two adjacent houses, both of which were damaged.  The destroyed frame house was owned by James T. Goode, who moved out of it four months ago. - Harris Photo."
TitMainTitle: Two fire fighters with ladders on roofs of house with 65 foot ladder extended in front of dormer, fighting fire at house belonging to James T. Goode next door, 7028 Frankstown Avenue, Homewood
